         "id": "SECTION_atom",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Hydrogen Family\n\nWhile conducting measurements of the hydrogen atom in <htdate0>, Francis William Aston noted that the values obtained for the weight of the hydrogen atom were greater than expected considering possible errors, which indicated there was something more in his measurements (<htcite0>).\n\n#### Recalling the Hydrogen Atom\n\nWhen we study the hydrogen atom, we learn that it has only one proton in its nucleus and one electron (<htcite1>), a fact that allows us to write its components in fractional form, as shown in **Calculation 1**.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b33db85b-0a38-4af8-bcee-f608e5442188",
                     "text": "Jolly, W.L.",
                     "page": "hydrogen",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "11",
                        "day": "27"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f5d420a5-02eb-4b7e-b318-05327b64a90f",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Evolution of Knowledge – hydrogen atom",
