      {
         "id": "SECTION_who",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### To be or not to be?\n\nBuilding on the definition of hydrogen and its isotopes, we can now generalize this information to other atoms and know when we are referring to a specific atom.\n\n#### Different Atoms\n\nTo know if we are dealing with a single type of atom or several types, we need to compare their atomic numbers—that is, the number of protons (<htcite0>).\n\nFor example, consider the hydrogen atom (H), which has a single proton in its nucleus, and the helium atom (He), which has two protons.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "19e9bbd7-ef72-462e-993b-70e6bbdc966b",
                     "text": "Britannica Editors",
                     "page": "atomic number",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "9",
                        "day": "6"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>Total Protons</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>He</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mn>H</mn></math></center></p> <p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>Total Protons</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>2</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn></math></center></p><p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>Total Protons</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn></math></center></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Comparison between the number of protons in helium and hydrogen atoms.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Calculation 1** shows us:\n- **Line 1**: We want to compare the number of protons between helium (He) and hydrogen (H) atoms.\n- **Line 2**: Helium has 2 protons, while hydrogen has 1.\n- **Line 3**: Consequently, the difference in the number of protons is not equal to zero.\n\nSince the result is a non-zero value, this means that helium and hydrogen are not the same type of atom.\n\n#### The Isotopes\n\nWhen working with the same type of atom, **Calculation** will always result in zero. However, the number of neutrons can vary, indicating that we are dealing with isotopes.\n\nFor instance, in a common hydrogen atom, the nucleus has no neutrons; on the other hand, deuterium (D) has one neutron. We can therefore determine if we are working with isotopes by comparing the number of neutrons in atoms of the same element in the following way:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>Total Neutrons</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>D</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mn>H</mn></math></center></p> <p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>Total Neutrons</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn> <mo>-</mo> <mn>0</mn></math></center></p><p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>Total Neutrons/mn> <mo>=</mo> <mn>1</mn></math></center></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Comparison between the number of neutrons in hydrogen and deuterium.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From **Calculation 2**, we can conclude:\n- **Line 1**: We want to compare the number of neutrons in deuterium (D) with that in a common hydrogen atom (H).\n- **Line 2**: The number of neutrons in deuterium (1) is greater than that in common hydrogen (0).\n- **Line 3**: Consequently, the result is different from zero.\n\nAs with **Calculation 1**, we observe that we are not comparing identical nuclei. However, despite the result being non-zero, this does not mean they are different chemical elements, since, having the same number of protons, both are forms of hydrogen.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: Almost the Same</b><br /><br />Look around you.<br /><br />Can you see something similar, but with slightly different characteristics?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_macro",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Macroscopic Comparisons\n\nIt's not just in the atomic world that we perceive seemingly identical things to be, in fact, different.\n\nLet's compare two circles shown in **Table 1** through a practice exercise.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table class=\"tawapukllay\" style=\"width: 50%;\"><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Circles</th></tr> <tr><td><div class=\"circle\" style=\"background-color:blue;width:5.5vw;height:5.5vw\"></div></td> <td><i class=\"fa-solid fa-circle\" style=\"color:red;font-size:6vw;\"></i></td></tr></table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Circles of the same diameter, but with different colors.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Are they the same?</b><br /><br />Graph 1 shows the light spectrum of the hydrogen atom. Notice that in the background, in the visible light region, there are shades of blue further to the left and red further to the right. This happens because light is organized by its wavelengths.<br /><br />Knowing that blue light has a wavelength of approximately 400 nanometers and red light, 700 nanometers, we can confirm we are talking about two circles, but not the same ones (i.e., not the same color).<br /><br />1. The first step is to measure the diameter of both circles. To do this, place the ruler at one edge and measure to the other edge for both circles, then subtract the results. In this step, you will see that they are the same type of geometric figure (circles of the same size).<br />2. Now, subtract the wavelength associated with the color of one circle from that of the other (Red – Blue = 700 – 400) and verify that they are not the same color, as the result will be different from zero.</div></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
